Marvel Television was, for a brief, bewildering moment in the grand cosmic scheme, an American [television production company](/Television_production_company). From its formation in June 2010 until its eventual, and frankly inevitable, folding in December 2019, it held the unenviable task of translating the sprawling narratives and vibrant, often absurd, characters from [Marvel Comics](/Marvel_Comics) into live-action and animated [television shows](/Television_series), alongside a smattering of [direct-to-DVD](/Direct-to-DVD) series.

Initially conceived as a distinct [division](/Division_(business)) within the larger [Marvel Entertainment](/Marvel_Entertainment) empire, Marvel Television was headed by the rather tenacious producer [Jeph Loeb](/Jeph_Loeb), who served as its [executive vice president](/Executive_vice_president) and the de facto shepherd of Marvel's small-screen ambitions. Its operational base was strategically located at an affiliate [ABC Studios](/ABC_Studios)' facility, a clear indication of its initial, and often strained, ties to the broadcast network [ABC](/American_Broadcasting_Company). Over its lifespan, this division navigated a labyrinth of partnerships, collaborating not just with ABC, but also the burgeoning streaming giants [Netflix](/Netflix) and [Hulu](/Hulu), and the cable channel [Freeform](/Freeform_(TV_channel)). The primary goal, or perhaps the existential burden, was to craft series that would ideally, if not always seamlessly, integrate into the ever-expanding tapestry of the [Marvel Cinematic Universe](/Marvel_Cinematic_Universe) (MCU) media franchise – that grand, [shared universe](/Shared_universe) meticulously curated by the film-centric powerhouse, [Marvel Studios](/Marvel_Studios). Beyond the MCU, Marvel Television also oversaw animated productions through its sister company, [Marvel Animation](/Marvel_Animation), and even ventured into the treacherous waters of licensing, collaborating with [20th Century Fox](/20th_Century_Fox) to produce shows based on the [X-Men](/X-Men_(film_series)) franchise, such as the critically acclaimed [Legion](/Legion_(TV_series)) and the somewhat less acclaimed [The Gifted](/The_Gifted_(American_TV_series)).

The corporate landscape, much like the superhero narratives it adapted, was prone to seismic shifts. In August 2015, a significant restructuring saw Marvel Television and [Marvel Animation](/Marvel_Animation) cleaved from [Marvel Studios](/Marvel_Studios), which itself was integrated into [Walt Disney Studios](/Walt_Disney_Studios_(division)). This left Marvel Television under the direct purview of [Marvel Entertainment](/Marvel_Entertainment) and its then-CEO, [Isaac Perlmutter](/Isaac_Perlmutter). However, this separation proved to be a temporary reprieve from the inevitable. By October 2019, the division was formally transferred back under the umbrella of [Marvel Studios](/Marvel_Studios) and, a mere two months later, was unceremoniously folded into its cinematic counterpart. The name "Marvel Television" now exists as a phantom limb, a mere production [label](/Marvel_Television_(Marvel_Studios_label)) used by [Marvel Studios](/Marvel_Studios) for its television endeavors, a stark reminder that even in the world of capes and powers, corporate restructuring is the ultimate villain.

